        <section id="faq" class="content-section faq-section">
          <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>Why is first quarter moon better for observing than full moon?</h3>
            <p>First quarter moon (and last quarter) provides dramatically superior observing compared to full moon because of shadows cast along the terminator—the line dividing lunar day from night. At quarter phase, sunlight strikes the Moon at a low angle, creating long shadows that emphasize topography: crater walls cast dark shadows revealing depth and structure, mountain peaks throw dramatic shadows across plains, and rilles appear as dark trenches rather than faint lines. Full moon receives direct overhead sunlight that eliminates shadows and flattens terrain, washing out detail in harsh glare. Additionally, full moon is painfully bright without filters, causing pupil constriction that reduces observable detail. The 4-10 day old waxing crescent and first quarter (and equivalent waning phases) offer the most rewarding lunar observing with rich shadow play revealing maximum three-dimensional detail. Serious lunar observers specifically avoid full moon, focusing efforts on the days before and after quarter phases when terminator features shine.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>What magnification is best for lunar observing?</h3>
            <p>Optimal lunar magnification ranges from 50x to 200x depending on aperture, atmospheric conditions, and feature size. For general lunar touring showing the entire disc or large regions, use 50x-80x magnification—this provides wide-field context, comfortable viewing, and works in average seeing conditions. For detailed crater studies examining terraces, central peaks, and wall structure, employ 100x-150x magnification on stable nights. For fine details like rilles, small craterlets, and mountain textures, push to 150x-200x on nights with excellent seeing (steady atmosphere). Maximum useful magnification equals roughly 50x per inch of aperture (2x per millimeter)—a 6-inch telescope maxes around 300x, but atmospheric turbulence typically limits practical use to 150-200x. Start at lower magnification to locate features, then increase power to resolve details. During poor seeing (shimmering, boiling image), stick with 80-100x; during exceptional seeing (crisp, steady image), push higher. Most satisfying lunar observing happens at 100-150x where detail and image stability balance optimally.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>Are lunar filters necessary for telescope observing?</h3>
            <p>Lunar filters are highly recommended but not strictly necessary—they dramatically improve viewing comfort and reveal subtle details by reducing the Moon's intense glare. The Moon at quarter phase or fuller appears painfully bright through telescopes, especially at magnifications above 100x, causing pupil constriction, eye strain, and loss of dark adaptation for subsequent deep sky observing. Neutral density lunar filters (also called moon filters) block 80-95% of light, dimming the view to comfortable levels that allow extended observation without eye fatigue. This comfort enables you to observe longer and notice finer details invisible in harsh glare. Variable polarizing filters offer adjustable dimming from 1% to 40% transmission, letting you optimize brightness for different lunar phases, magnifications, and apertures. Moon filters cost $15-$40 and thread into eyepiece barrels—every telescope owner should have at least one neutral density filter. Alternatives include observing at dusk when the Moon is lower in brightness, or during thin crescent phases (1-3 days old) when brightness is manageable. Without filters, many observers find full moon and gibbous phases too bright for comfortable viewing above 100x magnification.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>Can I see the Apollo landing sites with my telescope?</h3>
            <p>No, backyard telescopes cannot resolve Apollo landing sites, lunar modules, or American flags—the objects are far too small relative to the Moon's distance. The lunar modules measure roughly 4 meters across; at the Moon's distance of 384,000 km, they subtend just 0.002 arcseconds. Even the largest professional telescopes can theoretically resolve only about 0.04 arcseconds, and atmospheric turbulence limits Earth-based telescopes to approximately 0.5-1.0 arcsecond resolution. To resolve 4-meter objects on the Moon requires resolution of 0.002 arcseconds—impossible from Earth's surface. However, NASA's Lunar Reconnaissance Orbiter, orbiting just 50 km above the Moon, has photographed Apollo sites in remarkable detail, showing lunar modules, rovers, astronaut paths, and equipment. What you CAN see through backyard telescopes: the general landing site regions (like Mare Tranquillitatis where Apollo 11 landed, or Fra Mauro for Apollo 14), though these are distinguishable only as ordinary lunar terrain. Observing these regions while knowing human history occurred there adds special significance, even if the evidence remains invisible. The smallest features visible in backyard telescopes measure approximately 1-2 km across under excellent conditions with 200-300x magnification.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>What are the best eyepieces for lunar observing?</h3>
            <p>Lunar observing benefits from eyepieces providing 80x-200x magnification with wide apparent fields of view (60-70 degrees) and good eye relief (15mm+). Calculate required focal lengths by dividing telescope focal length by desired magnification: for 100x on a 1000mm telescope, use a 10mm eyepiece (1000÷10=100). Recommended eyepiece types: wide-field designs like Explore Scientific 82-degree series, Televue Nagler, or budget-friendly 68-degree ultra-wide angles provide immersive lunar vistas where large craters fill the field impressively. For detailed work, quality orthoscopic or planetary eyepieces (Baader Classic Ortho, Explore Scientific 52-degree) deliver sharp, high-contrast images with minimal aberrations. Zoom eyepieces (8-24mm or 7-21mm) offer convenient magnification changes for scanning (low power) to detailed study (high power) without changing eyepieces—useful for following features along the terminator. Eye relief matters for comfortable viewing: eyepieces with 15mm+ eye relief allow relaxed positioning without pressing your eye against the lens. Recommended focal length set for lunar work: 25mm (low power scanning), 10mm (medium-high detail), and 6mm (high power for fine features). All eyepieces should have good coatings to reduce internal reflections that degrade lunar contrast.</p>
          </div>

          <div class="faq-item">
            <h3>How do I identify specific lunar features?</h3>
            <p>Identifying lunar features requires a good lunar map or atlas matched to your telescope's view orientation, understanding of lunar phases and geometry, and systematic observing technique. Start with a planisphere or lunar map showing major maria (seas) and prominent craters—free apps like SkySafari or websites like VirtualMoon Atlas overlay feature names on real-time lunar phases matching exactly what you see through your eyepiece. Remember that telescope views invert or mirror images: refractors and SCTs show upside-down views; Newtonian reflectors show right-side-up but mirror-reversed. Note the terminator position (day/night boundary) which moves approximately 12 degrees per day, revealing different features nightly. Begin with conspicuous landmarks: Mare Crisium (isolated oval sea on eastern limb), Copernicus crater (bright rays radiating across western hemisphere), Tycho crater (southern highlands with most extensive ray system), and Mare Tranquillitatis (smooth southeastern sea). Once you identify these anchors, navigate to nearby features using their spatial relationships. Work systematically: observe at similar magnification as your atlas shows (typically 50x-100x for wide views), follow feature chains, and note distinctive characteristics like central peaks, terraced walls, ray systems, or unusual shapes. Keep an observing log sketching feature positions to build familiarity. After several sessions, prominent features become recognizable friends you can locate without maps.</p>
